Oh, cauliflower – what can’t you do?

You roast to perfection.
You make spicy ‘wings‘.
You can be roasted whole.
You’re delicious in Banh Mi.
You make tacos better (somehow).

Seriously, I think I’m in love.

This 6-ingredient, 30-minute recipe is bound to wow your guests this holiday season (and beyond). Cauliflower mocks mashed potatoes beautifully, and it all starts by steaming your cauliflower until tender.

summary: How do normal people get enough protein while maintaining a reasonable calorie intake. via /r/Fitness
title: How do normal people get enough protein while maintaining a reasonable calorie intake. via /r/Fitness
body:
I’m a 21 year old male, 183cm/6 ft tall. I just went to gym and weighed myself at 88.6kg/195lb. The most I’ve ever weighed.

Now this is just barely overweight and not too much cause for concern, but I’ve been trying really hard fitness recently, 3 days of running 5km and 3 days of Phrak’s Greyskull LP Variant a week. I’m seeing improvement, but to see my weight slowly increase is very frustrating.

I know the science and that if I want to lose weight I need to eat less calories than I consume in a day. But if I plug in my details into a TDEE calculator like this one, it tells me I need to be eating 214g of protein a day. this seems like an insane amount to eat while trying to target a 2000 calorie diet. That’s 35 hard boiled eggs a day, or 700 grams of chicken breast. This is leaving me feeling really overwhelmed and I’m looking for any advice or understanding.



Submitted December 03, 2018 at 04:23AM by Thatzachary
via reddit https://ift.tt/2FX8W7H

reblog.comment:
I’m a 21 year old male, 183cm/6 ft tall. I just went to gym and weighed myself at 88.6kg/195lb. The most I’ve ever weighed.

Now this is just barely overweight and not too much cause for concern, but I’ve been trying really hard fitness recently, 3 days of running 5km and 3 days of Phrak’s Greyskull LP Variant a week. I’m seeing improvement, but to see my weight slowly increase is very frustrating.

I know the science and that if I want to lose weight I need to eat less calories than I consume in a day. But if I plug in my details into a TDEE calculator like this one, it tells me I need to be eating 214g of protein a day. this seems like an insane amount to eat while trying to target a 2000 calorie diet. That’s 35 hard boiled eggs a day, or 700 grams of chicken breast. This is leaving me feeling really overwhelmed and I’m looking for any advice or understanding.



Submitted December 03, 2018 at 04:23AM by Thatzachary

New Workouts!

So I got kind of used to the workouts I had originally created and decided I seriously needed some variation to keep my muscles uncomfortable. Now I’m going to alternate each week between my original set and my new set.

We’ll see how it goes! I’ll post my new set soon.
